stylometry:
Sensitivity Analysis is when you look at many variables in a table. For example if you have a problem where you are wanting to determine storage capacity, but there is a 5% storage cost that you have to pay for every item that sits there in the warehouse, a sensitivity analysis can help you by being able to show you how much you could store if the percentage was lower or higher. Sensitivity analysis can look at more than just two variables as well. The problem about the two lines of glue and we had to minimize cost by figuring out which production line to set up (1, 2 or both) sensitivity analysis could look at minimizing cost while factoring in the number of workers, if the production line was open or not and how much was produced on the line. 

SolverTable has been used to show how profit, or cost would change if the number of items produced changes. This is helpful in determining what would happen if your business and finances if you over, or under produce or over and under sell.
